# Codex Adversarial Review

Target: branch diff against c59a94a6d3bc51a1284c79f0270358fdaefb7e8a
Verdict: needs-attention

No ship: the hardening still permits protocol desynchronization and does not actually enforce the advertised line-size bound.

Findings:
- [high] Serialization failures silently drop a response and let later responses masquerade as earlier ones (runtime/daemon/ipc-server.ts:340-364)
  The response write serializes outside the try/catch that builds `response`; if `JSON.stringify(response)` throws for handler data such as a circular object or BigInt, `work` rejects before writing any line for that request. The new catch only logs and consumes the rejection, while `safePrevious` allows the next queued request to write normally. Because this newline protocol has no request IDs and promises one response per request in arrival order, a pipelined client can interpret request N+1's response as request N's response, while a single-request client can hang waiting for a line that will never come. The added H3 test explicitly accepts this lost-response behavior, so the regression is likely to persist.
  Recommendation: Handle serialization/write failures as part of the per-request response path: serialize inside a try/catch and either send a guaranteed-serializable `{ ok:false, error:"internal: response serialization failed" }` for that request, or destroy the socket and prevent later queued responses from being emitted on the same connection. Add a test that the first request gets an error or the connection closes, not that its response disappears.
- [medium] The line-size cap is bypassed whenever an oversized line arrives with a newline (runtime/daemon/ipc-server.ts:275-304)
  The cap only destroys the socket when `buffer.length > maxLineBytes && !buffer.includes("\n")`. If an oversized complete line arrives with a newline in the same data event, this condition is false and the code immediately slices and dispatches that line without any length check. The implementation also advertises bytes but measures UTF-16 string length after `setEncoding("utf8")`, so multibyte input can exceed the byte budget before the guard fires. This leaves the new `maxLineBytes` protection dependent on packet/chunk boundaries instead of enforcing the configured bound, allowing oversized JSON.parse and handler work despite the hardening claim.
  Recommendation: Enforce the cap on every extracted line before `processLine`, and enforce it on the residual buffer after the parse loop. Measure bytes with raw Buffer accounting or `Buffer.byteLength(..., "utf8")`, and add tests for an oversized newline-terminated line plus multibyte input.

Next steps:
- Fix the IPC response failure path so request ordering cannot be corrupted.
- Make `maxLineBytes` a real byte bound independent of newline placement and stream chunking.
